---
import AnswerCapsule from '../components/AnswerCapsule.astro';
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="LangChain4j Workflows: Implementation Guide">
  
  <AnswerCapsule 
    question="How do you implement an AI workflow in LangChain4j?" 
    answer="To implement a LangChain4j workflow, define an 'AiService' interface, configure a ChatLanguageModel (like OpenAI or Gemini), and use an 'AiServices' builder to bridge them. For complex logic, integrate a 'TokenStore' for memory and 'Tools' for external API execution."
  />

  <h2>LangChain4j vs. Traditional Java AI Libraries</h2>
  
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Feature</th>
        <th>LangChain4j</th>
        <th>Standard Spring/Java AI</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Memory Management</strong></td>
        <td>Declarative 'ChatMemory' interface</td>
        <td>Manual state handling</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Model Agnostic</strong></td>
        <td>Yes (Change provider in 1 line)</td>
        <td>No (Vendor lock-in)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Tool Calling</strong></td>
        <td>Native '@Tool' annotation</td>
        <td>Requires custom wrappers</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Step-by-Step Implementation</h2>
  <p>The core of a LangChain4j workflow is the <strong>AiServices builder</strong>. Unlike basic API calls, this creates a stateful conversation agent.</p>
  
  <pre><code>
  Assistant assistant = AiServices.builder(Assistant.class)
      .chatLanguageModel(model)
      .chatMemory(MessageWindowChatMemory.withMaxMessages(10))
      .build();
  </code></pre>

  [...continue for ~500 words using bullet points and bolding for key terms...]
</Layout>